posts.name: Tim Sieberg
posts.cooked: If you manually rotate the angle of each wheel, does the correct raw absolute encoder change values on the dashboard.  For example, if you rotate the back left module, does the back left raw encoder change values on the dashboard.  Do that for each module.  Your problem looks similar to one we had when our encoders were out of order or the encoders were not providing values because of either bad wiring or bad encoders.

posts.name: Josh (he/him)
posts.cooked:
A couple things I would recommend checking, based on struggles my team has had with swerve:

Are your absolute encoder magnets seated at a proper depth AND held in place with a retaining compound of some sort? That could cause “correct” encoder offsets to become incorrect if magnets move over time, or are giving bad readings due to improper magnet depth.

I would use the USB tab of your driver station to look at the value you are getting from your controllers with them in a netural position. If you don’t have a deadband set according to this, it could cause some issues like undesirable movement when not touching the controller sticks.

I would also re-verify your module locations. An error there could cause the wheels to want to go to a different setpoint than what you might expect to see.

It does appear that your modules are pretty slow to respond in terms of snapping to a commanded direction, so I wouldn’t rule out a PID issue, but in my opinion all of the above would be good to rule out prior to more effort tuning.

I imagine the YAGSL folks may catch this thread and try to help (and they are very helpful!), but it probably wouldn’t hurt to cross-post into their main thread: Yet Another Generic Swerve Library (YAGSL) v1 Release

ETA: I did open your code, and as set I believe your default drive command is driveFieldOrientedDirectAngle, which also may have a different behavior than you might be expecting when using the right stick compared to “standard” swerve code where left stick = translation and right stick  = rotation.

posts.name: Andy Gasser
posts.cooked:
I would also take a look at your AbsoluteDriveAdv command. I don’t think that’s from YAGSL.

In your video, you are doing stuff with the right stick like it’s supposed to do something. However, your command doesn’t really seem to use that input to control the wheels, there’s a bunch of logic with buttons.

In your module configurations, shouldn’t these be set to “inverted: True”? @nstrike am I wrong for mk4i? Not too familiar with YAGSL but these are inverted modules.

//github.com/alealbacam/YAGSLSwerve/tree/main/src/main/deploy/swerve/modules

posts.name: Josh (he/him)
posts.cooked: AbsoluteDriveAdv is a command in the latest YAGSL example, but if you look at the default drivebase subsystem command in their robot container you can see it’s not being used in lieu of driveFieldOrientedDirectAngle.

Pretty sure they’re supposed to be, but it depends on what the modules are reading. In general my advice is as follows.

Install and open FRC Web Components. FRC Web Components | YAGSL

Check your inversions. When to invert? | YAGSL

Set offsets to 0 in the JSONs and get the offsets Absolute Encoders | YAGSL

Ensure your conversion factors are right. (Please delete them from your module files if they are all the same and only use the one in pidfproperties.json ) Standard Conversion Factors | YAGSL

Tune your PID . How to tune PIDF | YAGSL

Test drive with driveFieldOrientedDirectAngle

posts.name: Josh (he/him)
posts.cooked:
driveFieldOrientedDriectAngleSim is a command meant to be used for simulation purposes, so I assume some errors get thrown if it’s run in non-sim situations.

We cleared out the logic statement inside the parentheses of drivebase.setDefaultCommand() and replaced that with our desired drive command, based on the above I believe you want to put driveFieldOrientedAnglularVelocity there.

Unfortunately it’s too late in the season for me to give all the help you require, as it seems like you need Java basics (which you can learn from codeacademy.com ) and WPILib basics with command based programming ( https://docs.wpilib.org ) and then you’ll have enough info to start going through this section of documentation.
